File:Artic American shirt (UBC).jpg|Man's hide jacket. The floral designs' stems feature "thorny" beadwork, typical of the Subarctic, [[Museum of Anthropology at UBC]]
</gallery>

===Northwest Coast===
{{Main|Northwest Coast art}} {{See also|Alaska Native art|Coast Salish art|Kwakwaka'wakw art|Haida argillite carvings}}
The art of the [[Haida people|Haida]], [[Tlingit people|Tlingit]], [[Heiltsuk]], [[Tsimshian]] and other smaller tribes living in the coastal areas of [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington State]], [[Oregon]], and [[British Columbia]], is characterized by an extremely complex stylistic vocabulary expressed mainly in the medium of woodcarving. Famous examples include [[Totem pole]]s, [[Transformation mask]]s, and canoes. In addition to woodwork, two dimensional painting, and after contact - silver/gold/copper engraved jewelry became important. 

